00:48:08.840 --> 00:48:11.400
AUDIENCE: I was wondering since
wildlife photography is

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:13.750
such a kind of an on-the-fly
kind of thing where you really

00:48:13.750 --> 00:48:17.000
have to capture things in the
moment, are you consistently

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.980
using shutter priority
and autofocus?

00:48:19.980 --> 00:48:23.410
Or how often do you go
just full manual?

00:48:23.410 --> 00:48:25.490
ANDY BIGGS: That's a really
great question.

00:48:25.490 --> 00:48:27.870
I'm all over the board,
depending on the scenario.

00:48:27.870 --> 00:48:31.430
So if I'm hypersensitive to
shutter speed, which is

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:34.100
usually when I want to slow the
shutter speed down, I'll

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:36.400
switch to shutter-speed
priority.

00:48:36.400 --> 00:48:38.550
I would say most of the time,
I'd be in aperture priority

00:48:38.550 --> 00:48:41.530
mode because that's what's
most important for me.

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:45.080
In recent years with
specifically Nikon cameras,

00:48:45.080 --> 00:48:47.370
they do a really good
job with auto ISO.

00:48:47.370 --> 00:48:50.660
So I'll shoot in manual mode,
I'll set my shutter speed, my

00:48:50.660 --> 00:48:54.460
f-stop, and I'll let it
choose the ISO for me.

00:48:54.460 --> 00:48:56.770
Unfortunately, Canon hasn't
figured that out very well

00:48:56.770 --> 00:48:59.310
yet, the exposure
compensation.

00:48:59.310 --> 00:49:02.520
But I'm kind of all over the
board is the answer.

00:49:02.520 --> 00:49:05.040
But I'd say 75% of the time,
I'm probably in aperture

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:05.800
priority mode.

00:49:05.800 --> 00:49:06.080
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:09.060
And autofocus?

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:10.200
ANDY BIGGS: Actually,
I'm always in

00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:12.020
continuous autofocus mode.

00:49:12.020 --> 00:49:18.440
And for anybody who has an
SLR with a rear autofocus

00:49:18.440 --> 00:49:23.710
capability, usually on Canons,
it says AF On--

00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:25.450
and actually Nikons
are the same--

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:28.120
AF On on the back, I prefer to
use the rear autofocus button,

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:31.100
not the shutter speed
autofocus button.

00:49:31.100 --> 00:49:34.570
Because I can leave it in
continuous or AI Servo mode

00:49:34.570 --> 00:49:38.630
and take my thumb off to stop
focusing whenever I want to.

00:49:38.630 --> 00:49:41.020
So I don't have to
switch modes.

00:49:41.020 --> 00:49:44.070
And the reason why I use the
rear autofocus button is that

00:49:44.070 --> 00:49:46.530
I look at it from a process
standpoint.

00:49:46.530 --> 00:49:48.870
I'm a process guy.

00:49:48.870 --> 00:49:52.300
Back basically when Leica
invented the first 35

00:49:52.300 --> 00:49:54.530
millimeter camera, we
had an aperture

00:49:54.530 --> 00:49:55.630
selection on the lens.

00:49:55.630 --> 00:49:57.700
We had a shutter speed
on the camera.

00:49:57.700 --> 00:50:00.470
And whatever the film speed
was, that's what it was.

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:03.220
And then in the '50s,
they developed

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:04.180
meters in the cameras.

00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:05.790
And they said, well, where
are we going to put the

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:07.490
functionality for the meter?

00:50:07.490 --> 00:50:08.870
Oh, let's put it on the
shutter button.

00:50:08.870 --> 00:50:11.630
OK, so now we've got two
functions in one button.

00:50:11.630 --> 00:50:14.870
In the late '80s, when autofocus
came out, hey, let's

00:50:14.870 --> 00:50:15.640
have autofocus.

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:17.090
Where are we going to put
the functionality?

00:50:17.090 --> 00:50:18.350
Hey, let's put it on
the shutter button.

00:50:18.350 --> 00:50:20.860
So now we've got three
functions, one button.

00:50:20.860 --> 00:50:23.850
So autofocus, metering,
and take the shot.

00:50:23.850 --> 00:50:27.570
And that just fries my brain
thinking about that.

00:50:27.570 --> 00:50:29.870
From a UI standpoint, it
just doesn't work.

00:50:29.870 --> 00:50:33.020
So I prefer to shoot with
autofocus on the thumb,

00:50:33.020 --> 00:50:36.400
because it's independent
of my forefinger.

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:37.240
Hope that helps.

00:50:37.240 --> 00:50:38.820
AUDIENCE: Can you say a few
words about the different

00:50:38.820 --> 00:50:40.130
countries in which
you operate?

00:50:40.130 --> 00:50:41.720
And the character
of each country?

00:50:41.720 --> 00:50:43.010
ANDY BIGGS: Yeah, yeah.

00:50:43.010 --> 00:50:46.210
So the differences between
the countries.

00:50:46.210 --> 00:50:46.950
So let me--

00:50:46.950 --> 00:50:49.210
I'll make a broad statement
first and say that I go to

00:50:49.210 --> 00:50:51.460
areas where there's
a lot of wildlife.

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:54.930
And wildlife exists where there
are not a lot of humans.

00:50:54.930 --> 00:50:57.630
So typically more remote
locations--

00:50:57.630 --> 00:51:03.490
Kenya, Tanzania, Botswana,
South Africa, Namibia.

00:51:03.490 --> 00:51:05.570
Rwanda's in there, even though
that's a very densely

00:51:05.570 --> 00:51:07.030
populated country.

00:51:07.030 --> 00:51:09.870
And the Virunga Mountains are
basically an island amongst a

00:51:09.870 --> 00:51:13.120
sea of people, where the
mountain gorillas are.

00:51:13.120 --> 00:51:14.990
I only travel to areas
that are what I

00:51:14.990 --> 00:51:16.130
consider to be safe.

00:51:16.130 --> 00:51:18.360
Because I'm a father and
a husband as well.

00:51:18.360 --> 00:51:19.940
I want to come home.

00:51:19.940 --> 00:51:22.310
So it's very important to me.

00:51:22.310 --> 00:51:28.800
So usually, we get to places
that are remote.

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:31.910
We fly into a major city and
we fly out the next day.

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:33.370
And we get out in the
middle of nowhere.

00:51:36.260 --> 00:51:38.490
Most of my safaris are
split between--

00:51:38.490 --> 00:51:43.990
I'd say Kenya, Tanzania, and
Botswana, which are very, very

00:51:43.990 --> 00:51:47.450
easy places to get to,
politically stable.

00:51:47.450 --> 00:51:50.140
I know Kenya had some issues
a couple years ago.

00:51:50.140 --> 00:51:52.710
But really, on the whole, these
are very, very, very

00:51:52.710 --> 00:51:54.530
stable places.

00:51:54.530 --> 00:51:57.210
In other words, I'm not running
trips to West Africa,

00:51:57.210 --> 00:51:58.995
Nigeria any time soon.

00:51:58.995 --> 00:52:01.400
So East Africa is
a broad brush.

00:52:01.400 --> 00:52:06.040
East Africa is more wide open
savannah, where you have more

00:52:06.040 --> 00:52:09.620
grazing herding animals,
wildebeest and zebras.

00:52:09.620 --> 00:52:12.680
You get the wildebeest
migration, 2 million

00:52:12.680 --> 00:52:15.380
wildebeests, 450,000 zebras--

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:17.470
really, really big.

00:52:17.470 --> 00:52:19.690
Southern Africa tends
to be smaller

00:52:19.690 --> 00:52:20.930
congregation of animals--

00:52:20.930 --> 00:52:24.770
same species, just smaller
congregations and more

00:52:24.770 --> 00:52:25.990
intimate experiences.

00:52:25.990 --> 00:52:30.180
Because East Africa typically
works off of a national park

00:52:30.180 --> 00:52:33.170
method, where you pay fees to
be in the park, as well as

00:52:33.170 --> 00:52:33.730
other people.

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:35.060
And you'll see them.

00:52:35.060 --> 00:52:36.230
Southern Africa--

00:52:36.230 --> 00:52:39.010
South Africa, Botswana--

00:52:39.010 --> 00:52:42.430
tend to work off of a game
reserve, private game reserve,

00:52:42.430 --> 00:52:45.670
concession kind of a model
where a given camp has

00:52:45.670 --> 00:52:47.900
exclusive access to an area.

00:52:47.900 --> 00:52:53.290
And you'll see very few, if any,
vehicles within a day.

00:52:53.290 --> 00:52:54.680
Fees are a lot higher
in Southern

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:57.410
Africa than East Africa.

00:52:57.410 --> 00:52:59.480
I would say it's a fair
statement to say that most of

00:52:59.480 --> 00:53:02.010
my safari travelers will
start off with a

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:04.590
Tanzania or Kenya safari.

00:53:04.590 --> 00:53:07.030
They'll get interested and say,
this is a lot of fun.

00:53:07.030 --> 00:53:11.190
And they'll end up doing a
Botswana safari later, because

00:53:11.190 --> 00:53:13.580
it's a little bit more
of a commitment

00:53:13.580 --> 00:53:15.370
in time to get there.

00:53:15.370 --> 00:53:18.235
Financially, as well,
it's more expensive.

00:53:18.235 --> 00:53:23.830
But the species are virtually
the same everywhere that I go.

00:53:23.830 --> 00:53:26.210
So the question is, how did I
start the safari business and

00:53:26.210 --> 00:53:29.460
put together the first safari?

00:53:29.460 --> 00:53:30.960
I'm a networker.

00:53:30.960 --> 00:53:36.110
My personality is really driven
around talking to

00:53:36.110 --> 00:53:38.240
people and engaging
with people.

00:53:38.240 --> 00:53:42.790
And I knew Michael Reichmann,
who owned Luminous Landscape

00:53:42.790 --> 00:53:46.390
website, which is a nature
photography, a

00:53:46.390 --> 00:53:48.200
very popular site.

00:53:48.200 --> 00:53:51.140
I emailed him and said, hey,
let's put a safari together.

00:53:51.140 --> 00:53:52.220
He said, that sounds great.

00:53:52.220 --> 00:53:54.920
So that helped me build up a
name in the industry with

00:53:54.920 --> 00:53:56.600
somebody that was well known.

00:53:56.600 --> 00:53:59.570
And then it kind of
went from there.

00:53:59.570 --> 00:54:08.070
I was very fortunate in that I
was able to follow the same

00:54:08.070 --> 00:54:10.970
trajectory that digital
photography took at the same

00:54:10.970 --> 00:54:13.980
time that baby boomers were
starting to retire or cutting

00:54:13.980 --> 00:54:15.960
back on their work commitment.

00:54:15.960 --> 00:54:18.920
So international travel
was made easier

00:54:18.920 --> 00:54:19.940
10 or 15 years ago.

00:54:19.940 --> 00:54:21.070
It's just gotten easier
and easier and

00:54:21.070 --> 00:54:22.380
easier every decade.

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:25.460
But really, I'd say the late
'90s started getting really

00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:27.640
easy to a lot of these
places that I go.

00:54:27.640 --> 00:54:29.730
Digital photography
was on the rise.

00:54:29.730 --> 00:54:33.160
I bought my first pair of
digital SLRs in 2002, the

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:34.700
original D30 Canon.

00:54:34.700 --> 00:54:36.540
Paid three grand
each for them--

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:40.420
three autofocus points,
awesome.

00:54:40.420 --> 00:54:43.880
And I was seeing my customers
doing the same thing.

00:54:43.880 --> 00:54:46.670
People were getting
reinvigorated by digital

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:47.290
photography.

00:54:47.290 --> 00:54:49.440
Oh, I shot film but I stop
shooting in the '80s.

00:54:49.440 --> 00:54:52.360
Something like that was
usually the story.

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:56.860
Most of my travelers are either
empty nesters slash

00:54:56.860 --> 00:55:02.940
baby boomers, or high tech, one
kid or no kids, younger

00:55:02.940 --> 00:55:07.580
30s, late 20s into the 30s,
early 40s, kind of that

00:55:07.580 --> 00:55:11.360
demographic, and just a high
interest in digital

00:55:11.360 --> 00:55:13.420
photography that didn't
exist before.

00:55:16.320 --> 00:55:18.400
It's all about networking.

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:21.310
So I really appreciate you
guys coming out today.

00:55:21.310 --> 00:55:24.860
I wanted to be very mindful of
just one hour so that you can

00:55:24.860 --> 00:55:27.730
get back to your normal
daily life here.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:29.540
So thanks, guys, for
having me out here.

00:55:29.540 --> 00:55:33.340
[APPLAUSE]

